<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-428-031  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 428 031.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  August 1990 v22 n8 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Checklist for security checkup.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Steinhart, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Securing data against disasters, theft, and corruption of data isessential for any company.andP;  The core of any security plan isbacking up of files onto a tape or diskette.andP;  A disastercontingency plan should be in place.andP;  Have a procedure forhandling mini-disasters such as accidentally erasing an importantdocument; this includes having on hand disk recovery utilities.andO;Carefully hire and train employees and be sure they knowmanagement cares about data security and quality.andP;  Do not leave adischarged employee alone after the employee has been told aboutthe discharge.andP;  Guard against fraud by identifying computeroperations that are at risk and rotate employees doing those jobs.andO;Develop ways to track errors.andP;  Control forms.andP;  Personal computersshould be shut off and locked at the end of the working day.andO;Protect against viruses by not using software from bulletinboards, using only software that comes with its original,shrink-wrapped packaging, and checking the size on the directoryof a very small program that claims to do a big job.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityFraudComputer VirusesDisaster PlanningPersonnelBack-Up Procedures.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>